sala, SE-75310, Sweden.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-7\">\n                7\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Li+P&amp;cauthor_id=41126356\">Ping Li</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"School of Food Science and Biotechnology, Zhejiang Gongshang University, Hangzhou, 310018, China. ping-biology@outlook.com.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-8\">\n                8\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Li+L&amp;cauthor_id=41126356\">Lanjuan Li</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"State Key Laboratory for Diagnosis and Treatment of Infectious Diseases, National Clinical Research Center for Infectious Diseases, China-Singapore Belt and Road Joint Laboratory on Infection Research and Drug Development, National Medical Center for Infectious Diseases, Collaborative Innovation Center for Diagnosis and Treatment of Infectious Diseases, The First Affiliated Hospital, School of Medicine, Zhejiang University, Hangzhou, 310003, China. ljli@zju.edu.cn.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-9\">\n                9\n              </a><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Jinan Microecological Biomedicine Shandong Laboratory, Jinan, 250021, China. ljli@zju.edu.cn.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-10\">\n                10\n              </a><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Research Units of Infectious Disease and Microecology, Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences, Beijing, China. ljli@zju.edu.cn.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-11\">\n                11\n              </a></sup><span>, </span></span><span><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term=Yao+M&amp;cauthor_id=41126356\">Mingfei Yao</a><sup><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"State Key Laboratory for Diagnosis and Treatment of Infectious Diseases, National Clinical Research Center for Infectious Diseases, China-Singapore Belt and Road Joint Laboratory on Infection Research and Drug Development, National Medical Center for Infectious Diseases, Collaborative Innovation Center for Diagnosis and Treatment of Infectious Diseases, The First Affiliated Hospital, School of Medicine, Zhejiang University, Hangzhou, 310003, China. mingfei@zju.edu.cn.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-12\">\n                12\n              </a><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Jinan Microecological Biomedicine Shandong Laboratory, Jinan, 250021, China. mingfei@zju.edu.cn.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-13\">\n                13\n              </a><span> </span><a target=\"_blank\" title=\"Research Units of Infectious Disease and Microecology, Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences, Beijing, China. mingfei@zju.edu.cn.\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41126356/?fc=None&amp;ff=20251101161525&amp;v=2.18.0.post22+67771e2#full-view-affiliation-14\">\n                14\n              </a></sup></span>\n  </p></div>\n          <p>\n    Affiliations\n</p>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n          <span>\n  <span>\n      PMID:\n  </span>\n    <strong>41126356</strong>\n</span>\n        </li>\n        <li>\n          <span>\n  <span>\n      PMCID:\n  </span>\n    <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12542167/\">\n      PMC12542167\n    </a>\n</span>\n        </li>\n        <li>\n          <span>\n  <span>\n      DOI:\n  </span>\n    <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1186/s40168-025-02204-9\">\n      10.1186/s40168-025-02204-9\n    </a>\n</span>\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n        <p>\n  Item in Clipboard\n</p>\n      </div>\n      <div>\n<h2>\n  Improving fecal transplantation precision for enhanced maturation of intestinal function in germ-free mice through microencapsulation and probiotic intervention\n</h2>\n<p><span>\n        <span><span>Furong Ba</span><span> et al.</span></span>\n  </span>\n      <span>\n        Microbiome<span>.</span>\n      </span>\n        <span>\n          2025<span>.</span>\n        </span>\n</p>\n      </div>\n  <div>\n      <h2>\n        Abstract\n      </h2>\n            <div>\n    <p>\n        <strong>\n          Background:\n        </strong>\n      Fecal microbiota transplantation (FMT) has emerged as a widely used treatment for various diseases. While previous efforts have focused on selecting \"super donors\", the precise modulation of donor microbiota to enhance FMT efficacy remains a critical challenge. This study aimed to develop strategies to modify donor microbiota to promote gastrointestinal development and maturation in germ-free mice. Probiotic Pediococcus pentosaceus Li05 (Li05) was used as gut microbiota modulator to establish a healthier donor fecal microbiota, and a microencapsulation method was applied to ensure high bacterial viability during gastrointestinal tract transition.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n        <strong>\n          Results:\n        </strong>\n      Probiotic intervention initially altered the stability of the gut microbiota but eventually fostered a more complex bacterial interaction network and established a new equilibrium within 14 days. Transplantation of encapsulated Li05-modulated fecal microbiota significantly promoted epithelial development, improved barrier function, and altered the colonic transcriptome profile. These effects were found to be more dependent on the abundance of some bacterial genera instead of their co-occurrence network, and the key functional bacterial genera associated with these benefits were believed to be Parabacteroides, Parasutterella, Lachnoclostridium, Muribaculum and Desulfovibrio. Notably, both encapsulation and probiotic modulation played critical roles in enhancing the functional efficacy of these key bacterial genera, and the community composed of key functional bacteria demonstrated an antagonistic relationship with other bacterial communities. Moreover, encapsulated Li05-modulated fecal microbiota induced dramatical changes in host lipid metabolism, especially the bile acids and their derives. Sporobiota gained the function of promoting epithelium development gene expression only after Li05-modulation since high abundance of Lachnoclostridium was introduced.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n        <strong>\n          Conclusion:\n        </strong>\n      These findings underscore the importance of encapsulation and donor microbiota modulation in FMT and provide valuable strategies for improving transplantation precision and outcomes.\n    </p>\n            </div>\n    <p>\n        <strong>\n          Keywords:\n        </strong>\n      Pediococcus pentosaceus Li05; Bile acids; Fecal microbiota transplantation; Gut microbiota; Intestinal function; Microencapsulation; Sporobiota.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <p>\n    © 2025. The Author(s).\n  </p>\n  <p>\n  <a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/disclaimer/\" target=\"_blank\">PubMed Disclaimer</a>\n</p>\n  <div>\n    <h2>\n      Conflict of interest statement\n    </h2>\n    <p>Declarations. Ethics approval and consent to participate: The approval for the animal experiment (ethics code permit no.: 20231476) was acquired from the Tab of Animal Experimental Ethical Inspection of the First Affiliated Hospital, Zhejiang University School of Medicine. Consent for publication: Not applicable. Competing interests: The authors declare no competing interests.</p>\n  </div>\n      <div>\n        <h2>\n          Figures\n        </h2>\n        <div>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/933aad158b9e/40168_2025_2204_Fig1_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/48070a4f1af5/40168_2025_2204_Fig1_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 1\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 1\n    </strong>\n    <p>Dynamic changes of gut microbiota after Li05 supplement in mice. <b>a</b> Gut microbiota co-occurrence networks with respect to Li05 supplement time in mice of L group and N group. In the networks, each node indicates a genus (colored according to the phylum), and its size indicates degree. Red and blue edges indicate positive and negative correlations between connected nodes, and the width of edges represents the magnitude of the correlation. Histograms show the degree distributions of nodes. <b>b</b>–<b>f</b> Topological features of gut microbiota co-occurrence networks, including number of nodes (<b>b</b>), number of edges (<b>c</b>), average degree (<b>d</b>), clustering coefficient (<b>e</b>), number of hub nodes (<b>f</b>), modularity (g), and number of modules (<b>h</b>). The N and L groups are indicated by blue and red, respectively. <b>i</b> The temporal changes of bacterial genera based on the Markov chain models were evaluated. The genera transition probabilities of consecutive feces collection points from absence to presence (inflow) or vice versa (outflow) were estimated to identify persistence colonizing genera and transient colonizing microbes</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/1a8a29f90252/40168_2025_2204_Fig2_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/a632ac8bc3ca/40168_2025_2204_Fig2_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 2\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 2\n    </strong>\n    <p>Effects of encapsulated FMT on receiver mice. <b>a</b> Schematic representation of experimental design. Fecal microbes’ suspension was treated to GF mice directly or after microencapsulation, the GF mice were treated twice on day 1 and day 3, while the control mice were treated with saline. Feces were collected on day 4 and day 14. <b>b</b>, <b>c</b> Body weight and colon length on day 14 after FMT of each group. <b>d</b> Representative photographs of colon H&amp;E, AB/PAS, and Lgr5<sup>+</sup>/Ki67<sup>+</sup>staining (Scale bar = 50 μm).<b> e</b>, <b>h</b> Quantification of colonic crypt depth (<b>e</b>), AB/PAS<sup>+</sup> cells (<b>f</b>), Lgr5<sup>+</sup> cells (<b>g</b>), and Ki67<sup>+</sup> cells (<b>h</b>). <b>i</b> Relative expression of colonic tight junction proteins related genes <i>Tjp 1</i>,<i> Cldn4</i>, and <i>Ocln</i> after FMT. <b>j</b> Volcano plot of differential differentially expressed genes (DEGs) between eLF and LF group. Red and blue dots represented upregulated and downregulated genes in eLF group compared to LF group, and gray dots represented nondifferential gene. <b>k</b> Correlation analysis between mice characteristics and colonic transcript profiles. Positive correlations are represented in red, and negative correlations are represented in blue. Significant differences are denoted by *<i>P</i> &lt; 0.05. Data are shown as the mean ± SD. Significant differences are denoted by *<i>P</i> &lt; 0.05, **<i>P</i> &lt; 0.01; ***<i>P</i> &lt; 0.001; <i>ns</i> not significant</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/abf205b00d29/40168_2025_2204_Fig3_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/3737fd5f1f9f/40168_2025_2204_Fig3_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 3\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 3\n    </strong>\n    <p>Gut microbiota structure and key bacterial genera among mice after FMT. <b>a</b> Variation of α-diversity of gut microbiota among four FMT groups evaluated by Simpson index. <b>b</b> β-diversity of gut microbiota was analyzed by using PCoA based on the Bray–Curtis distance. <b>c</b> Relative abundance of the most abundant bacteria ranked top 15 at the genus level. <b>d</b> Relative abundance of five key bacterial genera abundant in encapsulated FMT groups, including<i> Parabacteroides</i>,<i> Parasutterella</i>,<i> Lachnoclostridium</i>,<i> Muribaculum</i>, and<i> Desulfovibrio.</i>\n<b>e</b> Positively correlated associations among mice characteristics, DEGs and key bacterial genera. Different letters a, b, and c indicate significant differences at <i>P</i> &lt; 0.05</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/e6c894ad191c/40168_2025_2204_Fig4_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/5a35f34b7449/40168_2025_2204_Fig4_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 4\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 4\n    </strong>\n    <p>Analysis of gut microbiota co-occurrence networks between FMT groups. <b>a</b> Gut microbiota co-occurrence networks among mice after FMT, each node indicates a genus, and its size indicates degree. Red and blue edges indicate positive and negative correlations, respectively. Histograms show the degree distributions of nodes. <b>b</b>–<b>h</b> Topological features of gut microbiota co-occurrence networks, including number of nodes (<b>b</b>), number of edges (<b>c</b>), average degree (<b>d</b>), clustering coefficient (<b>e</b>), hub nodes (<b>f</b>), modularity (<b>g</b>), and number of modules (<b>h</b>). The eNF and eLF groups are indicated by blue and red, and the NF and LF groups are indicated by light blue and light red, respectively</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/ad793bf95f02/40168_2025_2204_Fig5_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/d0ef76ebaa3b/40168_2025_2204_Fig5_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 5\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 5\n    </strong>\n    <p>Effects of Li05-modulated microbiota on recipient mice metabolism after FMT. <b>a</b> PLS-DA analysis of untargeted metabolomics results showed significant separation of metabolic profiles among groups. <b>b </b>Differential metabolites (FC &gt; 2 or FC &lt; 0.5, <i>P</i> &lt; 0.05) between groups were classified into 7 main categories, the largest number of differential metabolites was found to be in lipid metabolism. <b>c</b> Volcano plots showed the differential lipids and lipid-like molecules across groups, and top 10 molecules were labeled. Blue dots, gray dots, and red dots represented molecules downregulated, with no significant changes, and upregulated, respectively. <b>d</b> Heatmap of differential BAs and derivatives profile (left) and differential FAs and conjugates profile (right). The color from blue to red indicates that the abundance of metabolites ranged from low to high. <b>e</b>, <b>f</b> Relative concentrations of total BAs and total SBAs among mice after FMT. <b>g</b> The expression of <i>baiCD</i> gene in mice feces. <b>h</b>, <b>i</b> Network interactions between the differential bacterial genera and differential BAs (<b>h</b>) or differential FAs (<b>i</b>). Nodes represented bacterial genera (blue), key bacterial genera (dark blue), BAs (yellow), key BAs (orange), and FAs (pink), respectively. Node size represents the number of connections of a given genus or metabolite within the network. Significant differences are denoted by *<i>P</i> &lt; 0.05, **<i>P</i> &lt; 0.01; ***<i>P</i> &lt; 0.001; <i>ns</i> not significant</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/66ed67a47bbf/40168_2025_2204_Fig6_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/6d02d6f04958/40168_2025_2204_Fig6_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 6\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 6\n    </strong>\n    <p>Effects of sporobiota transplantations on gut epithelial development. <b>a</b> Two types of fecal spores from donor N and L groups were obtained and transplanted to GF mice. <b>b</b> Sporobiota transplantation didn’t change body weight among mice. <b>c</b> The representative photographs of colon HE, AB/PAS, and Lgr5<sup>+</sup>/Ki67<sup>+</sup>staining (Scale bar = 50 μm). <b>d</b>–<b>f</b> Quantification of AB/PAS<sup>+</sup> cells (<b>d</b>), Lgr5<sup>+</sup> cells (<b>e</b>), and Ki67<sup>+</sup> cells (<b>f</b>). <b>g</b> Relative expression of colonic tight junction proteins related genes <i>Tjp 1</i>,<i> Ocln</i>, and <i>Cldn4</i> after sporobiota transplantation. <b>h</b> Volcano plot of DEGs between LS and LF group. Red and blue dots represented upregulated and downregulated genes in LS group compared to LF group, and gray dots represented nondifferential gene. <b>i</b> Heatmap of upregulated DEGs in LS group compared to LF group. <b>j</b> Correlation analysis between upregulated DEGs and receiver mice characteristics. Positive correlations are represented in red, and negative correlations are represented in blue. Significant differences are denoted by *<i>P</i> &lt; 0.05, **<i>P</i> &lt; 0.01; ***<i>P</i> &lt; 0.001; ****<i>P</i> &lt; 0.0001; ns, not significant</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n            <figure>\n              <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/10b38a8e8792/40168_2025_2204_Fig7_HTML.jpg\">\n                <img src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7978/12542167/1799e14a1558/40168_2025_2204_Fig7_HTML.gif\" alt=\"Fig. 7\" />\n              </a>\n                <figcaption>\n    <strong>\n      Fig. 7\n    </strong>\n    <p>Effects of sporobiota transplantation on gut microbiota and metabolomic features in mice. <b>a</b> The relative abundance of the top 15 most abundant genera in gut microbiota from NS and LS groups after FMT. <b>b</b> The relative abundance of 5 key bacterial genera in mice from NS and LS groups on day 14. <b>c</b> Positively correlated associations among mice characteristics, DEGs and <i>Lachnoclostridium</i>. <b>d</b> The co-occurrence network of gut microbiota among mice after sporobiota transplantation. Histograms show the degree distributions of nodes of the networks. <b>e</b>–<b>k</b> Topological features of gut microbiota co-occurrence networks, including number of nodes (<b>e</b>), number of edges (<b>f</b>), average degree (<b>g</b>), clustering coefficient (<b>h</b>), number of hub nodes (<b>i</b>), modularity (<b>j</b>), and number of modules (<b>k</b>). <b>l</b> PLS-DA analysis of untargeted metabolomics results showed significant separation of metabolic profiles among C, LS, and NS groups. <b>m </b>A total of 1,436 differential metabolites (FC &gt; 2 or FC &lt; 0.5,<b> P</b> &lt; 0.05) between LS and NS groups were classified into 7 main categories, and the category with the largest number is lipids and lipid-like molecules with 343 molecules involved.<b> n</b> Heatmap of differential BAs and derivatives. The color from blue to red indicates that the abundance of metabolites ranged from low to high. <b>o</b>, <b>p</b> Relative concentrations of total BAs and total SBAs among mice of Control, NS, and LS groups. <b>q</b> The expression of <i>baiCD</i> gene in mice feces. <b>r</b> The correlation analysis between the key differential BAs and <i>Lachnoclostridium</i>. Significant differences are denoted by *<i>P</i> &lt; 0.05, **<i>P</i> &lt; 0.01; ***<i>P</i> &lt; 0.001;<b> ns</b> not significant</p>\n                </figcaption>\n            </figure>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n  <div>\n    <h2>\n      References\n    </h2>\n    <div>\n      <ol>\n  <li>\n    <ol>\n        <li>\n            de Vos WM, Tilg H, Van Hul M, Cani PD. Gut microbiome and health: mechanistic insights. Gut. 2022;71:1020–32.\n                  -\n                  <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8995832/\">\n                    PMC\n                  </a>\n                  -\n                  <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35105664/\">\n                    PubMed\n                  </a>\n        </li>\n    </ol>\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <ol>\n        <li>\n            Sorbara MT, Pamer EG. Microbiome-based therapeutics. Nat Rev Microbiol. 2022;20:365–80.\n                  -\n                  <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34992261/\">\n                    PubMed\n                  </a>\n        </li>\n    </ol>\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <ol>\n        <li>\n            Eiseman B, Silen W, Bascom GS, Kauvar AJ. Fecal enema as an adjunct in the treatment of pseudomembranous enterocolitis. Surgery. 1958;44:854–9.\n                  -\n                  <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/13592638/\">\n                    PubMed\n                  </a>\n        </li>\n    </ol>\n  </li>\n  <li>\n    <ol>\n        <li>\n            Porcari S, Benech N, Valles-Colomer M, Segata N, Gasbarrini A, Cammarota G, et al. Key determinants of success in fecal microbiota transplantation: From microbiome to clinic. Cell Host Microbe. 2023;31:712–33.\n   